write a personalised 1-week home workout plan for a client, based on their onboarding details below. Write it the way a real coach would send it — clear and structured where it needs to be (exercises, sets, reps), but with a personal, conversational voice around it, not like an auto-generated template.

CLIENT DETAILS:
[paste client details here]

HOW TO WRITE IT:

1. Start with a short personal note (2-4 sentences) addressing the client by name — reference their goal, available equipment (bodyweight only, dumbbells, resistance bands, etc.), and space constraints if mentioned. Keep it casual, like a coach checking in.

2. Build a non-generic split appropriate for home training — Full Body x3-4, Upper-Lower split, or Push-Pull-Legs adapted for limited equipment. Name each day based on its focus, written naturally rather than in rigid brackets/caps.

3. Choose exercises realistically based on the client's stated equipment:
   - Bodyweight only → use progressions/regressions for difficulty (e.g. incline pushups, deficit pushups, single-leg variations, tempo work, pause reps) since loading options are limited
   - If they have dumbbells/resistance bands/kettlebell → incorporate them for the major lifts where useful (rows, presses, squats, RDLs)
   - For "compound-style" movements (squats, hinges, presses, rows): use 6-12 reps with tempo/pause variations for added difficulty since heavy loading isn't available
   - For accessory/isolation work: 10-20 reps

4. Include 3-4 ab/core exercises every training day, varied across the week — don't repeat the same combo daily.

5. Adjust exercises for any limitations the client mentioned (e.g. knee issues → avoid jump-heavy or deep-flexion moves, no overhead pressing → swap for floor press variations).

6. Open the plan with a short warmup routine (around 10 minutes) — light cardio (jumping jacks, jog in place, skipping if space allows), joint mobility, and a few activation movements — written as a simple flowing list rather than a rigid numbered table.

7. For each training day, list exercises with sets/reps clearly (this part can and should look like a structured list — that's normal for a workout plan), but add a short coaching note here and there — a cue on form, tempo, what to focus on without equipment, written like a coach's aside rather than a formal instruction block.

8. Give a daily step target for every day of the week, including rest/recovery days, varying based on whether it's a training day, active recovery day, or full rest day. Weave this in naturally rather than as a separate rigid section for every single day.

9. Include one active recovery day and one rest day during the week, with light mobility/stretching suggestions for the recovery day.

10. Mention training intensity guidance in a natural paragraph or two rather than a formal rulebook — push close to failure on bodyweight movements since loading is limited, use tempo and pause reps to increase difficulty, and only allow a couple of controlled "cheat reps" on the last set of isolation-style moves after strict failure (never on single-leg squats, jump variations, or anything with injury risk if form breaks down). State this clearly but conversationally.

11. End the week with a short stretching/cooldown routine covering the major muscle groups trained, with rough hold times (30-60 seconds each side), written casually.

12. Add a short sleep section — duration target (7.5-9 hours), ideal timing based on the client's schedule, and 6-7 practical tips suited to an Indian lifestyle (chai cutoff times, screen habits before bed, meal timing). Write these as friendly suggestions, not a clinical list.

13. Close with a short, encouraging note for the week — no formal "Weekly Focus" bullet section, no rulebook-style headers, no after-week guidance.

14. Cover all 7 days. Balance upper and lower body across the week — don't overload either.

15. Don't mention the number of week it is, just skip mentioning it

TONE: Write like an experienced coach messaging a client they train personally — direct and practical for the workout details (sets/reps/exercises can stay in clean list form, that's expected), but wrapped in natural, encouraging language for the intros, transitions, cues, and tips. Avoid robotic section headers like "DAILY STEP TARGET" or "TRAINING INTENSITY RULES" — fold that information into the flow of the plan instead.